@145  = ~Well, the days we've spent together have been interesting, <CHARNAME>. In a short time, you've accomplished more than I could have imagined. More than I could have done on my own (for better or worse). I never thought I'd end up here when I left Cormyr.~
//t2.r0 + t2.3
@146  = ~I don't think this is the best time to talk, Dusk. It's best if we leave it for later.~
//t2.r1 *
@147  = ~Cormyr, huh? I remember you mentioned something about being a messenger of peace. Was that where you were assigned that role?~

//t2.r0 = t2.3 FIN
@148  = ~So be it, <CHARNAME>. I had planned to talk about my past and interrogate you a bit about yours, but I suppose I'll figure out the latter as we go along on our adventure, don't you think? Let's continue with the journey.~

//t2.r1 *
@149  = ~That's right. I come from a noble family, the Aldants. In the past, my ancestors fought alongside the knights of the Purple Dragon order. Our natural enemies were creatures of formidable power...~
@172  = ~Liches... sorcerers who sold their souls for immortality. An enmity that dates back to the Age of Nether. Many of my blood fell fighting against those vile undead...~ 
@150  = ~Although I know about the history of the Aldants, I'm not very proud of it. At least, not anymore. You could say that I'm the weakest link of the family... and, to top it off, the last descendant. Although... I think that's fine.~
@151  = ~But I must snap out of these thoughts. As I was saying, I grew up in Cormyr and enlisted in the Purple Dragon Army. The land, as you may already know, is ruled by the Obarskyr family. They are good regents, <CHARNAME>. They care about their people and about peace in Faerûn.~
@173  = ~That's why they designated a small detachment to see what was happening between Tethyr and Amn.~
@152  = ~The rumors of an imminent war were becoming more frequent... even some battles had already taken place in the Forest of Mir, with Tethyr forces attacked by mysterious skirmishes.~

//t2.r2 ** ir a @157 + t2.4
@153  = ~This is boring, Dusk. Do you want to hear about my lineage? I think it would be more fun than this nonsense you're telling me.~
//t2.r3 *** IR A @158 (CONT)
@154  = ~Some Town Criers in Athkatla are shouting about the rumors you speak of. Cormyr's interest in the matter confirms the truth of the possibility of war you mention.~
//t2.r4 **** IR A @156 (FIN)
@155  = ~Uh... look at the time, Dusk. We should probably continue the journey. We can continue the conversation another time, right?~

//t2.r4 **** = t2.6 FIN
@156  = ~So be it, <CHARNAME>. I won't bother you again about your lineage. As for my past, I suppose you can judge it for yourself when the time comes.~

//t2.r2 ** ir a @161
@157  = ~Ehrm... well, <CHARNAME>, as you say. I suppose you'll be able to judge my past with time, as the time between us goes by.~

//t2.r3 ***
@158  = ~We knew little of the authenticity of such tales. Our mission was clear: to find out what this mystery was all about and to avoid a war, if possible. Tethyr and Amn have always been, in all, reasonable nations. A large-scale war would not be good for trade, which they both boast about here in Amn. As you'll see, I already had a plan to confront the nobles.~
@171  = ~But... first, we had to get to Tethyr... and for that... we had to flank the Troll Hills through the Giant Plains...~
//t2.r3.1 ***
@159  = ~Are you well, Dusk? You suddenly turned pale.~
//t2.r3.1 *** ir a @161
@160  = ~I'm fine, <CHARNAME>, don't worry. If you don't mind, I'll tell you about those events another time. Now, I think we could talk about something else, don't you think?~

//t2.r2 **
@161  = ~Now it's your turn... are you in the mood to talk about your lineage?~

//t2.r5 ir a @144
@162  = ~Hmm... I think it's better if we don't talk about this, Dusk. I don't feel like it. Besides, I think you'll figure it out for yourself.~
//t2.r6 ******
@163  = ~The reason why Irenicus, the mage who caused the disaster at the Waukeen's Promenade, is interested in me is because of my lineage: I am one of Bhaalspawns.~

//t2.r6 ******
@164  = ~Bhaal? He's... the Lord of Murder... I sensed a divine aura in you, my friend... but I never imagined it was something like this... Does that mean you're some kind of demigod?~ ~Bhaal? He's... the God of Murder... I sensed a divine aura in you, my friend... but I never imagined it was something like this... Does that mean you're some kind of demigoddess?~
//t2.r6 ****** todas van a @168
@165  = ~That's right, Dusk. I'm a demigod, capable of turning you into a lizard if I please. See the finger movements I'm making? Your scales are about to start growing.~ ~That's right, Dusk. I'm a demigoddess, capable of turning you into a lizard if I please. See the finger movements I'm making? Your scales are about to start growing.~
@166  = ~I don't believe I'm any more special than any creature you know, Dusk. But let me tell you this: being a descendant of Bhaal has brought me a lot of trouble. I suppose I would prefer to be related to some pompous nobleman as someone once told me.~
@167  = ~I don't feel like a deity. In fact, right now what I feel is thirst and sleepiness. Could you buy a drink for this descendant of Bhaal, Dusk?~

//t2r7
@168  = ~Very funny, <CHARNAME>. Although I admit you've made me smile.~
@169  = ~But I see that your divine heritage is no joke. The mere presence of such a powerful being as Irenicus proves it. I imagine you have no idea why he's after you... but if it helps, <CHARNAME>, I promise to stay by your side until we find out what that fool is up to.~
@170  = ~Well... we've had a good chat. My sincerest apologies, my <LADYLORD>. We'd better continue our journey.~

