@357  = ~Knowing you, I imagine you were speechless, eh?~
@358  = ~I am interested to know what your response was, Dusk.~
@359  = ~Certainly, the question caught me off guard. Instantly, she confessed to having heard my conversation with Zaranda in Darromar.~
@360  = ~She apologized, with tears in her eyes, but immediately demanded an explanation.~
@361  = ~'I am only human, Celine,' was my response. She was perceptive enough to know what I meant.~
@362  = ~'Love cannot be measured by time, Dusk,' she responded. 'Love cannot be measured, because my love for you overflows with joy and pain... joy for having you and pain for the fear of losing you... But that is life.'~
@363  = ~'I do not pretend to be wise enough to say that I have all the answers, my love. But what I do know is that I want to spend as much time as possible by your side, because being with you feels like home to my heart...'~
@364  = ~'Now that I have said this... I understand that marriage is only a formality... If you do not want to, we do not have to do it.'~
@365  = ~For some reason, at that moment I made up my mind, <CHARNAME>. I told her that I loved her and that we would marry upon reaching Shilmista.~
@366  = ~We embraced under the reddish rays of the sunset in Tethyr... I still feel how her arms wrapped around my neck and how her hair danced in my face.~
@367  = ~Forgive me, <CHARNAME>... I think I will continue my story another time.~
@368  = ~<CHARNAME>, what is your opinion on marriage?~


// **********************************************
// P_Dusk_T10

@571  = ~*ahem* So... <CHARNAME>, are you... interested in knowing how my story continues?~

@572  = ~Upon arriving at Shilmista, I requested an audience with King Elbereth to ask for Celine's hand in marriage. Although her parents had died many years ago in combat against the orcs, I believed it was the right thing to ask the protector of the forest elves.~
@573  = ~For the convenience of the elven king, he saw it as a positive thing to forge ties with Cormyr. I told him that marriage was not a political strategy.~
@574  = ~Immediately, the ceremony was planned. Hm... I barely have any memory of it. I've tried to forget the elven customs since then. Besides... those kinds of details are not relevant.~
@575  = ~The point is that neither Celine nor I were people of crowds... as soon as we could, we planned a trip to the north of the forest.~

@369  = ~So, <CHARNAME>, do you want to know about my wedding?~
@370  = ~Well, well, Dusk. Yes, tell me everything.~
@371  = ~Hm... We don't have time for this, Dusk.~
@372  = ~We arrived at Shilmista and were warmly welcomed by its inhabitants. Immediately, I requested an audience with King Elbereth to ask for Celine's hand in marriage. Although her parents had died many years ago in combat against the orcs, I thought it was the right thing to do with the protector of the forest elves.~
@373  = ~Elbereth was surprised, but saw it as a positive thing to forge ties with Cormyr. I told him that marriage was not a political strategy. He just smiled and said: 'I am aware of that.'~
@374  = ~The ceremony was immediately planned. It was wonderful. Elves have beautiful customs, <CHARNAME>. In endless ecstasy of forest's splendor, amidst the flickering, aglow fireflies, they danced with joyful rapture, constantly capturing their love for nature.~
@375  = ~However... Celine and I were not of the sort who favor crowds... henceforth, we did plan a journey towards the northern parts of the woods.~
@376  = ~We spent our first nights in a place called The Hill of the Stars.~
@377  = ~The place is almost on the borders of the forest, so the sky, being on the heights, was immense.~
@378  = ~Amidst the vast expanse of space, we saw the endless sea of stars ablaze. The evening sky's beauty, pure and bright, a shining, celestial guide, its lights illuminated us and we were, for an instant, a beacon in the darkness of the night.~
@379  = ~I kissed Celine. And in that moment... in that moment...~

@576  = ~I thought I had everything I needed... that I was filled inside with something they call... happiness. I was a fool to think that...~

@380  = ~I was naive enough to believe that happiness would be eternal.~
@381  = ~Why, Dusk? What happened?~
@382  = ~You're right, Dusk. You are naive. Happiness is not eternal. But tell me, how does your story continue?~
@383  = ~*sigh* Forgive me, <CHARNAME>. I will continue... I will continue on another occasion.~

// **********************************************
// P_Dusk_T11

@577  = ~I will begin the story of the event that led me to become a Wizard Slayer, <CHARNAME>.~

@384  = ~I will begin the story of the event... the event that led me to become a Wizard Slayer, <CHARNAME>.~
@385  = ~Of course, Dusk. Please continue.~
@386  = ~Perhaps another time, Dusk. It's not a good time now.~
@387  = ~A few weeks after my wedding, a messenger arrived from Darromar. In fact, the messenger himself was one of the royal advisers of Zaranda.~
@388  = ~His name was Darvin, a little man who was afraid of his own shadow. He requested to speak with me and Celine regarding our visit to Tethyr and our audience at the castle.~
@389  = ~When we were in Darromar and I had my audience with Zaranda, Darvin was among those present, hearing everything I had to say about it.~
@390  = ~Darvin told us that the rumors of a war were not rumors, but a promise. The Zhentarim sought the destruction or weakening of both nations to establish a monopoly in the south of Faerûn.~
@391  = ~I inquired about the regents of Tethyr and the griffins they had sent to Amn. Darvin commented that the discovery of the Zhentarim plot was after the sending of the griffins and that the organization's actions were imminent.~



@392  = ~"Why come to us?" we asked. Darvin said that direct interference from someone in Tethyr or Amn could escalate the war, but if a foreigner, either from Cormyr or Shilmista, intervened, they could prevent a bloodshed.~
@393  = ~A bit strange, don't you think? Tell me what happened next, Dusk.~
@394  = ~From the way you're telling it, that Darvin didn't give you a good feeling, did he?~
@395  = ~The truth is that Darvin didn't convince me much. However, he produced a note with the emblem and royal seal of Zaranda. That convinced me to keep listening.~
@396  = ~What Darvin wanted from us was an incursion to the north of the forest, crossing the Valashar River, leaving the forest behind until we found a camp, apparently of merchants.~
@397  = ~According to Darvin, those were the Zhentarim mercenaries sent to carry out targeted assassinations in Tethyr, with the purpose of framing Amn in the process and thus unleashing the war.~

@398  = ~"How will we know if we're not attacking the wrong people?" Celine asked intelligently.~
@399  = ~Darvin said we would find Zhentarim emblems in their hideouts.~
@400  = ~I was familiar with what the Zhentarim emblem looked like, so recognizing it wouldn't be a problem.~
@401  = ~We didn't have to think much about it, <CHARNAME>. So, after a few hours of planning, we set off northward.~
@402  = ~And...? Dusk, what happened?~
@403  = ~Don't tell me... it was a trap.~
@404  = ~I'm almost done with my story, <CHARNAME>. It's better if we continue it another time.~

// **********************************************
// P_Dusk_T12

@578  = ~<CHARNAME>, I will continue with my story where we left off.~

@405  = ~<CHARNAME>, if you want, I can continue with my story from where we left off.~
@406  = ~Yes, Dusk. Please continue.~
@407  = ~After a few nights of travel, we had the camp in sight.~
@408  = ~Celine, with her elven sight, noticed that it was empty.~
@409  = ~I knew it... it was a trap, wasn't it? Tell me, what did Celine do?~
@410  = ~Continue, Dusk. What happened next?~
@411  = ~I asked her to stay hidden while I investigated the mercenary camp. She would cover me with her bow in case of an ambush.~
@412  = ~Strangely, even though we were on the plains, the silence grew as I approached the tents and the extinguished campfires.~
@413  = ~I had a bad feeling, <CHARNAME>. Nevertheless, I searched through those ragged belongings for signs of the Zhentarim emblem. No matter how much I looked, I couldn't find anything.~
@414  = ~I waited a few minutes before leaving the camp and returning to Celine, but I decided to take one more look.~
@415  = ~In front of an extinguished campfire, I saw something shining on the ground, as if it were a gold coin.~
@416  = ~As I approached, a loud noise stunned me, and sparks blinded me. I had activated a magical trap...~
@417  = ~I tried to scream to warn Celine not to approach, but I was muted. The trap included, apparently, a silence spell.~
@418  = ~Celine, seeing that I had been paralyzed by that ruse, ran towards me. That's when, out of nowhere, a dimensional door opened.~

@419  = ~As the sparks and smoke from the teleportation spell vanished, the image of Darvin lay in front of us.~
@420  = ~But he was not the frail little man he had appeared to be. He stood tall, and his once bright eyes were now filled with an otherworldly blackness.~
@421  = ~"It's wondrous how easy it is to deceive the hearts of the merry", he said. Even his voice had changed. It was deep and accentuated, and I couldn't place what region it was from. But that's to be expected... human mages lose touch with reality, even their own humanity.~
@422  = ~Celine tried to aim her bow at him, but Darvin's lips moved faster: Celine, like me, suffered a magical paralysis through a spell cast by the mage.~
@423  = ~"The arrival of both of you in Darromar was more than propitious. Undoubtedly, an event that meant a change of plans for our Order", he said.~
@424  = ~I tried to speak, but I was still silenced by the spell. The mage moved his fingers and the spell dissipated, but I was still paralyzed.~
@425  = ~"Who are you? I'm sure Darvin isn't your name..." I asked.~
@426  = ~The mage laughed macabrely. "It's a name too common in Tethyr, isn't it?" He became serious and his black eyes alternated between me and Celine. "I am Anthagar, the Necromancer."~
@427  = ~"What do you want from us, Anthagar? If you wanted us dead, you would have done it already, wouldn't you?" I asked.~
@428  = ~He smiled. "It's true, Captain... But my master has taken a particular interest in this... union between elves and humans."~
@429  = ~"It's true that we seek war between Amn and Tethyr..." he continued. "Trying to deceive the nobles was proving more difficult than we expected. Zaranda is not an easy person to deceive. And, as if by magic, you appeared."~


@430  = ~"The rumors of war had started some time ago," he said. "The best part of it all is that it wasn't started by us. We don't know who or what it was, nor do we care."~
@431  = ~"All we want is for chaos to be unleashed upon the land and for death to hover in the air. Only then can we achieve our purpose."~
@432  = ~As the bastard continued his story, I began to realize that the paralysis spell was weakening with each passing second. I concentrated all my will on breaking those invisible chains.~
@433  = ~Celine noticed this and tried to do the same. But Anthagar noticed and warned her: "What are you doing, elf?!" he raised his hands. "Bah! Anyway, I only need one of you alive."~
@434  = ~I now know that he was casting a magical death spell against Celine. At that time, still ignorant of this, I knew that whatever Anthagar cast would result in my wife's death. So it was then that I finally broke free from his spell.~
@435  = ~I quickly struck him with my quarterstaff. The blunt blow hit his chest and I managed to knock him down before he finished his spell.~
@436  = ~The bastard pulled out a magic wand from his sleeves and fired a projectile at me. The magical damage hit me directly in the chest.~
@437  = ~I fell backwards to the ground, watching as Anthagar stood up. "It seems it will be you, after all", he said.~

@438  = ~With his voice as dark as death, he began to conjure. I knew it would be my end... but he said that only one of us had to die... in a way, I was glad it was me and not Celine.~
@439  = ~But... in that instant, Celine's scream filled the air. She broke out of her paralysis and threw herself in front of the spell...~
@440  = ~Oh, Dusk... don't tell me that...~
@441  = ~Celine fell face down in front of me. Anthagar seemed surprised. I saw him try to move his hands, but an expression of pain escaped his lips. Apparently, the blow I gave him with the staff had worn him down.~
@442  = ~"It seems... Captain... that you will have to deal with the weight of history..."~
@443  = ~"Keep this in mind: if your wife says your name, the curse will be broken... but in doing so, the effect will be immediate death..."~
@444  = ~"Love is cruel, don't you think?" After saying this, he disappeared into the shadows of a black portal, his cursed laughter fading into the darkness.~
@445  = ~I quickly took Celine into my arms. She was still alive... but... but...~
@446  = ~The sparkle in her eyes had disappeared.~
@447  = ~Her breathing seemed stable, as did her vital signs... but she didn't respond to my voice...~
@448  = ~AAnthagar had cursed her...~
@449  = ~<CHARNAME>, I can't continue... it's better... it's better to leave it for another time, a final time...~

// **********************************************
// P_Dusk_T13 - FINAL

@450  = ~<CHARNAME>, I will proceed to narrate the last chapter of my story...~
@451  = ~I carried Celine in my arms and traveled as fast as possible back to Shilmista.~
@452  = ~At the borders, some elven guardians were waiting for us, so in a way, we were no longer in danger of another ambush.~
@453  = ~Once in the heart of the forest, Elbereth herself oversaw the situation: many elven clerics and sorcerers had answered the King's call.~
@454  = ~Elven wisdom unveiled the mysteries of the curse in just one night. The spell was something very particular and personal. Whoever created it did so with us in mind.~
@455  = ~Celine's soul had been extinguished by said curse. To restore it, a highly dangerous ritual had to be performed in a cursed place.~
@456  = ~The location had to show signs of wild, demonic, or necromantic magic. Elbereth mentioned that the closest place to perform such a ritual was the Ruins of the Trinity Castle.~
@457  = ~I didn't pay attention to the details of why, <CHARNAME>. I can only imagine that some malevolent ritual related to demons or undead was performed there.~
@458  = ~Those imaginings were confirmed when I arrived at the site.~
@459  = ~Dusk, did you go to the ruins? I imagine it must have been very dangerous.~
@460  = ~You're crazy, Dusk. Conjuring a ritual in those ruins is but an invitation to disaster.~
@461  = ~I understand… and what happened?~


@462  = ~Well... the idea was to carry out said ritual in the ruins of the castle...~
@463  = ~Anyway... the traits of the curse, as you may have imagined, consisted of nullifying the life force of the target. The affected person could not speak, nor do anything on their own. It was as if they were a puppet without strings.~
@464  = ~The nature of the curse could be broken with a counter-spell carried out through a ritual. One of the elven sorcerers mentioned that there was a slight possibility that Celine could break the curse herself, but I knew that if that happened, Celine would die... Or at least that's what the bastard Anthagar had said.~
@465  = ~We only had seven days and seven nights before the curse consumed Celine's life energy.~
@466  = ~The clerics of Shilmista told me that the curse could only be cleansed by someone close to the cursed. A loved one or a family member.~
@467  = ~Celine had no blood relatives, and even if she did, I would not have allowed them to carry out the ritual. It was something that depended on me. It was my responsibility.~
@468  = ~I have knowledge of these types of situations, Dusk. The cost of such a ritual is not something to be taken lightly.~
@469  = ~It was a risky decision, Dusk. I don't see how you could risk your life for a lost cause.~
@470  = ~I had to do it, <CHARNAME>. And I was aware of the possible consequences.~
@471  = ~And the consequences were fatal... If I failed to execute the ritual correctly, the same arcane energy would absorb both Celine's and my life. But... if I did it correctly, it would only cost mine.~
@472  = ~Your life?! By Candlekeep, Dusk. To give your life for an unknown magical ritual? That's extreme.~
@473  = ~What one does for love... Please, Dusk, continue.~

@474  = ~...~
@475  = ~After a few days, we arrived at Trinity. Elbereth provided a band of warriors and explorers as an escort, but I demanded that they stay outside the Ruins. If I didn't come out within a few hours, they were ordered to march back to Shilmista.~
@476  = ~I entered what must have been the royal hall of the castle. Once it would have been splendid in the sunlight, and surely enjoyed happiness and harmony... But now... it was nothing more than the skeleton of a dark and malevolent structure.~
@477  = ~Silence reigned in every corner and shadows seemed to lurk around any living presence that entered those chambers.~
@478  = ~In that place, the moonlight ceased to exist as black clouds reigned relentlessly. The darkness there is eternal, with no respite or break in pace...~
@479  = ~But I had to snap out of this terrifying scenario. I had with me that which would save my love... The counter-curse: An elvish parchment from the Forest of Shadows.~
@480  = ~One of the elven sorcerers trained me to read the counter-curse parchment that I was to execute. He told me that upon entering cursed ground, I must read it in front of Celine.~
@481  = ~No one was sure what would happen during the process, but they did know that if successful, it would deliver my life energy to revitalize Celine. And if I failed, we would both immediately die there, in the shadows of Trinity...~
@482  = ~*sigh* Damn it, <CHARNAME>. Forgive me, but I can't continue... I thought I could do it... but I can't... I can't...~
@483  = ~Dusk, what happened? If you're alive, it's obvious the ritual didn't work...~
@484  = ~Clearly, you failed in your endeavor, Dusk. Did you read the parchment wrong and cause your wife's death?~
@485  = ~I'm certain whatever happened wasn't your fault, Dusk.~
@486  = ~The ritual never got to be executed, <CHARNAME>...~
@487  = ~It's true... I failed... I failed my wife...~
@488  = ~Oh, <CHARNAME>... but yes... it was my fault.~
@489  = ~Celine was right in front of me... her gaze empty, lifeless, like the environment we were in.~

@490  = ~I began to read the scroll... and with each word, my voice seemed to rise to the heights, resonating in every corner of the darkness.~
@491  = ~My vision began to blur and I began to glimpse shadowy figures on the horizon, as if the emissaries of death were coming for me.~
@492  = ~The prayer was about to end and my heart, terrified by my impending fate, began to tremble.~
@493  = ~It was then that I turned my gaze to Celine. Her eyes were full of tears and the sparkle was restored. Everything... everything happened very quickly... However, there was also a sense that time had ceased to pass.~
@494  = ~The image of Anthagar appeared in my mind and his warning returned: "If your wife says your name, the curse will be broken... but in doing so, the effect will be death...".~
@495  = ~I intended to speed up the ritual... but... my words were broken... finally... by her voice... She said:~
@496  = ~“Ardusk…”~
@497  = ~As my voice faltered, silence flooded in a heavy stillness, a deepening din.~
@498  = ~Those visions I had of death had faded away, and there was only her, illuminated by the torches' fire.~
@499  = ~She smiled sweetly and collapsed...~
@500  = ~Before... before she fell to the ground I held her in my arms...~
@501  = ~“Celine... Celine... I'm here... I'm here, by your side...”~
@502  = ~With her last breath, she caressed my face... and her eyes closed... forever...~
@503  = ~I kept talking to her... but my words were lost in the shadows... and no one was listening to me. No one was listening to me.~
@504  = ~Dusk, I'm sorry for your loss...~
@505  = ~It wasn't your fault, Dusk... you did what you could.~
@506  = ~I lost track of time... I don't know how many hours passed... I couldn't say, as the nights in that cursed place are eternal...~
@507  = ~Finally... I took her body back to Shilmista. Elbereth himself took care of the solemn services. The ceremony was... beautiful.~
@508  = ~As a consequence of this... I gave my life to become a Wizard Slayer. Anthagar is out there... and I still need answers as to why he did what he did...~
@509  = ~I intend to find their Order... and destroy each one of its members...~
@510  = ~Count on me, Dusk. When the time comes, I'll be by your side.~
@511  = ~Hm... it sounds dangerous, Dusk. But, anyway, I wish you the best of luck.~
@512  = ~Thank you, <CHARNAME>. I knew I could count on you. And thank you for listening to me...~
@513  = ~Luck has nothing to do with this, <CHARNAME>. Nevertheless, thank you for listening to me...~



@514  = ~An artifact you say? Although it sounds tempting, it doesn't convince me of what you're saying, monster. However, I will follow <CHARNAME> and if you betray us... you will pay with your life.~

@515  = ~Jon Irenicus, today will be the last day of your miserable existence! Your attempt to accumulate power has failed. You will fall and we will obtain the glory! Come on, <CHARNAME>, let's end this abomination...~

@516  = ~Ha! How is it possible that a drow has been caught so easily by these weaklings? In my opinion, such ineptitude should be punished with death...~

@517  = ~*whisper* This is comical... it was us who annihilated this wretch's 'belongings.' While it was a pleasure to do so, I think we've been deceived, <CHARNAME>.~

@518  = ~An alliance with this... filth? Although it offers us a good deal, I don't think it's worth it, <CHARNAME>. If it were up to me, I'd decapitate it right here. It doesn't deserve any other fate...~

@519  = ~We have an opportunity here, <CHARNAME>. Irenicus is getting closer and closer. Although I don't trust this... demon. Let's do what she wants and then... 'deal' with her.~

@520  = ~There's nothing more pitiful than fanatics blinded by their beliefs... Although, in this case, it's very literal for my taste.~

@521  = ~Pray to whichever god you want, dog... No one will save you from death. Leave it to me, <CHARNAME>! I'll enjoy his agony...~

@522  = ~<CHARNAME>, I believe I can handle the task. If you want, send me. I'll threaten him and make him give up those papers that this... red fool wants so badly.~

@523  = ~I hope we're assigned to assassinate Mae'var, <CHARNAME>. That scourge doesn't deserve to live for another second...~

@524  = ~It's a lot of effort if you ask me. However, it never hurts to dispatch one or two slavers. I'll do it with pleasure if that's what you want, <CHARNAME>.~

@525  = ~Slavery is a very profitable business. But it's a business for cowards. And there's nothing that gives me more pleasure than taking out cowards who think they're strong. Come on, <CHARNAME>. Let's find that lair and stir up some trouble.~

@526  = ~I don't think the 'reward' was worth it. But hey, it's been a pleasure to crush those pusillanimous fools.~

@527  = ~What else can you expect from a courtesan? For these types of people, the word 'responsibility' doesn't exist.~

@528  = ~I must admit, I'm a little curious as to why he's done all this. But, again, who cares about the desire of a lunatic?~

@529  = ~It's strange, I don't sense any magical energy from this lad. However, it's clear that he's not in his right mind.~

@530  = ~This place is disgusting. The smell of fish is abundant. The tiles are sticky... Damn it, <CHARNAME>, these places you bring us to...~

@531  = ~I never thought I'd see a silver dragon. I wonder if it has any artifacts that are worth something...~



// ENTRADAS DE DIARIO JOURNAL ENTRIES

@210001 = ~Dusk Aldant: The Shilmist Armor

After a brief conversation with Dusk, he mentioned that he has the possibility of recovering his combat armor, a chainmail that was delivered to a friend of his for repairs. We can find it in an abandoned house northwest of the Athkatla's Docks.~

@210003 = ~Dusk Aldant: The Shilmist Armor

We found Mathyus Davis, a strange elf with green hair. Our encounter led to another quest: the search of a Leprechaun named Michelson.
According to Mathyus, the little one would be wandering the streets of the port. We can recognize him by his red hair and green clothing.
Lastly, convincing him to return won't be easy. We'll have to use gold, beer... or make him laugh with a joke.
We'll see how the quest turns out.~

@210004 = ~Dusk Aldant: The Shilmist Armor

Finally, we found Michelson and were able to convince him to return with Mathyus. We should go back and claim our reward.~

@210009 = ~Dusk Aldant: The Renegades of Sothillis

Dusk has managed to resolve the conflict without bloodshed. Although he couldn't decipher the mystery of the Cormyr shield, he has recovered it and is now campaigning to give a home to the renegades of Sothillis. We must go to the Noble Order of the Radiant Heart in the Temple District of Athkatla and talk to Sir Ryan Trawl. Dusk believes he can provide a solution to the matter.~



